subSection.paragraph:
Crinum
× 
amabile
Donn ex Ker Gawl. (Amaryllidaceae)

is locally known in Thai as ‘phlap phlueng dok daeng’ or ‘giant lily’ (
Smitinand, 2014
). In 
Thailand
, the bulbs of this plant have been traditionally used as diuretics (
Bunyapraphatsara and Chokchaicharoenporn, 1999
). In addition, this plant species has been widely used in Vietnamese folk medicine as an emetic and a remedy for rheumatism and earache (
Pham et al., 1998
). Recent phytochemical investigations of this plant showed the presence of haemanthamine-, crinine-, lycorine- and galanthamine-type alkaloids (
Likhitwitayawuid et al., 1993
; 
Tallini et al., 2018
, 
2021
; 
Panthong and Ingkaninan, 2021
). Previous pharmacological evaluations of the extracts and phytochemicals from this plant revealed their cytotoxic, anti-malarial, anti-cholinesterase and anti-inflammatory potentials (
Likhitwitayawuid et al., 1993
; 
Diego et al., 2018
; 
Tallini et al., 2018
, 
2021
; 
Panthong and Ingkaninan, 2021
). However, the studies on phytochemicals and biological activities of this plant species have not much been reported.

The known alkaloids were identified as epibuphanisine (
12
) (
Viladomat et al., 1995
), (+)-bulbispermine (
13
), yemenine A (
14
) (Abdel-- Halim et al., 2004), ()-11-epihaemanthamine (
15
) (
Pabuççuoglu et al., 1989
), haemanthidine (
16
) (
Hohmann et al., 2002
), hamayne (
17
) (
Viladomat et al., 1994
), crinamine (
18
) (
Likhitwitayawuid et al., 1993
), 6-hydroxycrinamine (
19
) (
Viladomat et al., 1996
), buphanisine (
20
), flexinine (
21
), augustine (
22
) (
Pham et al., 1998
), epijosephinine (
23
) (
Chen et al., 2011
), augustamine (
24
) (
Ali et al., 1983
), ()-lycorine (
25
) (
Likhitwitayawuid et al., 1993
), 1- 
O
-acetyllycorine (
26
) (
Lamoral-Theys et al., 2009
), 1- 
O
-acetylisopseudolycorine (
27
) (
Evidente et al., 1984
), 1- 
O
-acetylnorpluviine (
28
) (
Campbell et al., 2000
), ungeremine (
29
) (
Ail et al., 1986
) and trisphaeridine (
30
) (
Sanz et al., 2007
) by spectroscopic (
1
H and 
13
C NMR, and HR-TOFMS spectra) data and by comparison of their experimental and reported values. Previous reports on the alkaloid constituents of 

C. amabile

included compounds 
18
, 
20
, 
22
and 
24–27
, and two alkaloid 
N
-oxide analogs of compounds 
20
and 
22
(
Likhitwitayawuid et al., 1993
; 
Tallini et al., 2018
, 
2021
). The two major 
types
of alkaloids isolated in the present work include the crinane- and lycorine-type alkaloids (
Tram et al., 2002
), with the first 
type
predominating.

Optical rotations were measured on a JASCO-1020 polarimeter. Electronic Circular Dichroism (ECD) was recorded on a JASCO J-810 spectropolarimeter. IR spectra were recorded in the ATR mode using a PerkinElmer FT-IR Spectrum 400 spectrophotometer. 1 H and 13 C NMR spectra were recorded at 25 ◦ C on a Bruker ASCEND 400 FT-NMR spectrometer, operating at 400 MHz and 100 MHz for 1 H and 13 C NMR, respectively. Chemical shift values are depicted as δ values in parts per million (ppm) and were indirectly referenced to tetramethylsilane (TMS) via the solvent residual signals δ H 7.24 and δ C 77.00 for CDCl 3 ; δ H 3.30 and δ C 49.50 for CD 3 OD. The coupling constants are expressed as J in Hz. HR-TOFMS spectra were measured with a Bruker micrOTOF-QII mass spectrometer, using electrospray ionization (ESI, positive ion mode) as the ionization technique. Unless otherwise indicated, column chromatography was carried out using Merck silica gel 60 (particle sizes less than 0.063 mm ) and Merck silica gel 60 RP-18 (particle sizes
0.040 –0.063 mm
). The slurry method of column packing has been employed. For thin-layer chromatography (TLC), Merck pre-coated silica gel 60 F 254 plates were used. Spots on TLC were detected under UV light and by spraying with anisaldehyde-H 2 SO 4 reagent and Dragendorff’ s reagent followed by heating.

The inhibitory activities of the crude extracts and isolated compounds on AChE and BuChE were conducted using Ellman’ s method ( Ellman et al., 1961 ) with minor modifications mentioned in the previous report (Chaichompoo et al., 2021). The enzymes and chemicals including AChE (from
Electrophorus electricus
), BuChE (from equine serum), galanthamine (as hydrobromide salt), 5,5 ′ -dithiobis (2-nitrobenzoic acid) (DTNB), bovine serum albumin (BSA), acetylthiocholine iodide (ATCI) and S -butyrylthiocholine iodide (BTCI) were purchased from Sigma-Aldrich (St. Louis, Missouri , USA ). Briefly, the enzyme solutions were prepared at 0.2 U/mL in 10 mM phosphate buffer solution (PBS, pH 8.0). The assay medium consisted of 140 μL of 10 mM PBS, 20 μL of the enzyme and 20 μL of the test compounds were mixed in a 96-well plate and shaken for 10 min. The reaction was initiated by the addition of 20 μL of a mixture of 5 mM DTNB, 0.1% BSA, and substrate (ATCI or BTCI) and was then incubated at room temperature for 5 min. The absorbance was measured using a microplate reader (Sunrise, Switzerland ) at a wavelength of 405 nm . The percentage of AChE inhibition was calculated by comparing the rate of enzymatic hydrolysis of ASCI for the sample to that of the blank (80% MeOH in buffer). The percentage of BuChE inhibition was similarly performed as described for AChE. Galanthamine was used as a positive control. All experiments were conducted in triplicate and IC 50 values were calculated by linear regression.
